# PR #10840: PS-68982 The GroupId when updated for the user should update in PermissionProject table for the same user.
**Tipo:** unknown
**Branch:** `wip/abdul/PS-68982` → `feature/Improv`

## Descripción
PS-68982 The GroupId when updated for the user should update in PermissionProject table for the same user. Before this change itt was fetching the non-updated GroupID from PermissionProject table and updating in the m_UserCache.

## Feedback de reviewers
[COMMENTED por @copilot-pull-request-reviewer[bot]]: ## Pull request overview

This PR addresses PS-68982 by ensuring that when a user’s `GroupID` (default security role) is updated, the corresponding `PermissionProject` (project permission) records are also updated so downstream reads don’t repopulate `m_UserCache` with stale group information.

**Changes:**
- Extended `UpdateUserProjectPermission(...)` with an optional `userGroupIdUpdated` flag intended to force rewriting permission rows with the user’s current `GroupID`.
- Added a new `UpdateUserProjectPermission(...)` call in `UpdateUsersFieldsInternalAsync(...)` when `GroupID` is present in the incoming `RecordChangeUser.Fields`.



<details>
<summary>Comments suppressed due to low confidence (1)</summary>

**Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/UserSystem.cs:2129**
* When `userGroupIdUpdated` is true, this condition forces *every* accessible project permission’s `GroupID` to be overwritten with `user.GroupID`, which will wipe out intentional per-project role overrides. The codebase already expects that changing a user’s default security role should only update project permissions that were using the previous default (leaving non-matching project roles unchanged), e.g. `Core/Tests/ProjectSight.Tests.ParallelIntegrationTests/Excel/Users/PropagateDefaultSecurityRoleToProjectsTests.cs` asserts non-matching project roles remain unchanged. Consider passing the previous default group id into this method and only updating permissions whose `GroupID` matches that previous value (or otherwise explicitly marked as “use default”), rather than blanket-updating all permissions.
```
                    permission.UserID = user.ID;
                    if (permission.GroupID == UserProjectPermission.USE_USER_GROUPID || userGroupIdUpdated)
                    {
                        permission.GroupID = user.GroupID;
                        permission.GroupName = user.GroupName;
                    }
```
</details>
[COMMENTED por @copilot-pull-request-reviewer[bot]]: ## Pull request overview

Copilot reviewed 1 out of 1 changed files in this pull request and generated 2 comments.



<details>
<summary>Comments suppressed due to low confidence (1)</summary>

**Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/UserSystem.cs:2129**
* `userGroupIdUpdated` currently forces `permission.GroupID`/`GroupName` to be overwritten for *all* accessible project permissions. This will wipe any project-specific security role overrides (and can also override role values explicitly supplied in the update request). Instead, only update PermissionProject rows that were implicitly using the user's *previous* default group (e.g., where the permission's GroupID equals the prior `user.GroupID`), leaving per-project role assignments untouched.
```
                    permission.UserID = user.ID;
                    if (permission.GroupID == UserProjectPermission.USE_USER_GROUPID || userGroupIdUpdated)
                    {
                        permission.GroupID = user.GroupID;
                        permission.GroupName = user.GroupName;
                    }
```
</details>
[CHANGES_REQUESTED por @kcostenbader]: In local testing, I am not seeing the behavior that this is attempting to fix. I have asked for clarification and update of the bug. Once we get that, we can determine whether this is an appropriate fix or not.
[Comentario en Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/UserSystem.cs:2620 por @Copilot]: This introduces a second call to `UpdateUserProjectPermission` when `GroupID` is present in `recordChange.Fields`. If `AnyProjectPermissionsChanged` is also true (and the default group is being edited), the method can run twice in the same transaction, adding extra DB work and potentially affecting counters like `user.ProjectPermissionsAdded`. It would be safer to compute `userGroupIdChanged` once (e.g. `recordChange.Fields?.ContainsKey(nameof(UserMaintenance.GroupID)) == true`) and call `UpdateUserProjectPermission` only once with an explicit flag, rather than in two separate blocks. Also, `TryGetValue(..., out var value)` is currently only used for its boolean result; use `out _` (or `ContainsKey`) to avoid the unused local.
[Comentario en Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/UserSystem.cs:2602 por @Copilot]: `userGroupIdUpdated` is derived from `recordChange.Fields.ContainsKey(GroupID)` rather than whether the value actually changed. This can trigger a full PermissionProject rewrite (one stored-proc call per project permission) even for no-op updates. Consider capturing the previous `user.GroupID` before applying `recordChange` and only running the PermissionProject update when the group ID transitions to a different value.
[Comentario en Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/UserSystem.cs:2622 por @Copilot]: This change introduces new behavior when a user's default `GroupID` changes without any explicit project-permission edits. There are existing integration tests for project permission GroupID updates, but none appear to assert that a default GroupID change correctly updates `PermissionProject` while preserving project-specific role overrides. Adding a targeted test for this scenario would help prevent regressions.

